eric pointed out some confusion: We should not be tracking CKF flags on the NSS side - or at least, generating the keys with all flags.

In the end, it won't matter - the Blink side is responsible for enforcing usages.

The example of why we shouldn't be doing this is a key being used to unwrap JWKs. NSS will never support JWK, so it will need to CKF_DECRYPT the JWK and then import that, but if this is used, it'll only have the CKF_UNWRAP.

If it won't let you supply no usages, supply all usages (that are valid for that key type) - eg: no sign/verify for AES keys.

At this point, we've fully downloaded a file to the Downloads folder and now we want to provide a reference to that file to the 'intent handler' script as a 'blob'... is that right?

Some questions...

* Does/should this file be visible in the downloads tray?

* Should this file be automagically deleted at some point or should it remain in the users Downloads folder?

Depending on the answers, things would probably be different in how to handle it. I think these answers to those questions, YES and NO, make for the simplest implementation with regard to blob handling. In particular the answer to the second question (dont automagically delete) makes the real difference.

Assuming for the moment we don't automagically delete these files...

I think you just want to send the full file path (not a blob url) to the WebIntentHost running in the recipient renderer process. And to use the WebBlob::createFromFile(full_file_path, file_size) method to create the blob, that method expects a FilePath as input. And that's it... no need to muck with blob storage controller and such.

If we do want automagic deletion... things would get a little more complicated... let me know if that's the behavior you really want.

else if any extension removes the bookmark shortcut

else
  return BOOKMARK_SHORTCUT_DISPOSITION_UNCHANGED

Why init last_ (an unsigned type) to the result of a subtraction (always a sketchy thing to do with unsigned types)?
IOW doing last_(0) would be no less correct, but less confusing.

However, using last_(0) has the down-side of the unobvious fact that the first run through WaitMultiple will populate [1,size) followed by 0.
If instead of tracking last_ you tracked next_start_offset_ then you could drop the -1 here (by  initializing to 0 here), and have a more expected order in the first run of WaitMultiple (and subsequent runs stay as obvious).  Plus, IMO, the calc of 
(i + next_wait_offset_) % synchronizers.size()
is slightly clearer than 
(i + last_signaled + 1) % synchronizers.size()

I disagree. Data races are never a good excuse for any design. Sorry.

Frankly speaking, I have done some designs where data races were "benign", i.e. in worst case produced only some incorrectly gathered statistics, and even this sometimes wakes me up as a nightmare. Here we make eviction decisions based on this data, which makes the matter very complex and hardly reproducible if a data race resulted in a very unusual code path.

Also, data races will be reported by data race detection tools, which we would need to suppress using annotations in our code, which is very complicated and requires a lot of expertise.

In the end, manual data privatization to threads is a commonly used pattern for optimization. We may incapsulate it into a single class that would be easier to update. Occasional inconsistencies when updating code may happen, of course, but at least it would be buried within the same small class.
So this code will need improving. Either this class here or the ProfilePolicyConnector must explicitly become an observer of the CloudPolicyStore and react when OnStoreLoaded() is fired.

It seems odd for the PrecacheFetcher to have knowledge of the database. AIUI, ideally PrecacheFetcher would just fetch URLs that it's told to fetch. What if the classes were reorganized like this:

- Make UnfinishedWork contain almost all the state of PrecacheFetcher, including the starting_hosts, the config_url, and the ConfigurationSettings itself if it's already been fetched. That way, the UnfinishedWork can represent the state right before precaching is started.
- Make PrecacheFetcher always take in an UnfinishedWork and develop its state around that, where UnfinishedWork could represent the state before precaching was even started.

Then, PrecacheManager could use PrecacheDatabase to check if any partially done UnfinishedWork was saved and use that if it exists, otherwise it could just create a new UnfinishedWork representing the state before any precaching is done, e.g. only the starting_hosts and stuff are set.

I don't think that you should include the path in the key. Instead, this function should return a map from process names to sums and sets of paths:

processName -> (sum, Set<processPath>)

This will make the processing easier (no need to do the split on line 47). More importantly, this will make the results better:

Suppose that you get a snapshot with the following CPU usage:

  /00/chrome: 0.5%
  /01/chrome: 0.5%
  /02/chrome: 0.5%
  ...
  /99/chrome: 0.5%

Your current code will report this as a Numeric:

  name: 'cpu:percent:chrome'
  full_paths: {'/00/chrome', ..., '/99/chrome'}
  avg: 0.5% (count: 100)

Whereas my proposal will give you:

  name: 'cpu:percent:chrome'
  full_paths: {'/00/chrome', ..., '/99/chrome'}
  avg: 50% (count: 1)

I believe that the latter is better because it more clearly shows that chrome uses 50% memory.

This is not the way to do it. You need to finalize the type argument vector.
Your 'basic type' is an unfinalized type with a null type argument vector. The vector may not be null anymore after finalization. Consider
class C<T> extends List<int>.
new C() results in an instance with a type argument vector of [int, dynamic].

or

class D extends List<int>

new C() results in an instance with a type argument vector of [int].

You cannot finalize the vector here. You need to do it before calling the constructor in the API code.

1) be designing our classes to use the underlying Mojo services for things like files and network access.
2) Design all of our I/O classes with an async IO model in mind, not a synchronous one.

There are multiple ways to fake out ffmpeg's transport interfaces if we go this route.  The simplest way would be to use a mojo service to get a data pipe and then just use the data pipe in a synchronous.  There are other ways (which usually involve a dedicated thread) to fake out ffmpeg so it feels that it is accessing data synchronously when it is actually async underneath at the transport implementation level.

3. Our old friend from (1) continues executing Trace(), and evaluates s_trace_buffer->buffer[blah].  **BOOM**

I am very concerned with this use of Input and Output terminology.  You are using them in a grammatically correct fashion, but it is in conflict with the way these terms are typically used in the context of streams.  Normally "Input" is for the side with a "Read" function so that you can input data into a program, and "Output" is for the side with a "Write" function so that you can output data from a program.  Here you have inverted the sense, and I suspect this will lead to confusion.  Why fight convention?

you might also consider using the terms "reader" and "writer", so you'd have pipe_reader_->Read(...) and pipe_writer_->Write(...).  that would be fairly conventional too.

This doesn't have to be fixed yet, but I'm not comfortable with the fault handling here yet. It seems like there's two possible kinds of faults:

1) the fault is related to the commit, and we need to move the commit aside rather than retry it, so that we don't keep repeating the same error.

2) the fault is infrastructure-related, rather than patch related, and we should (a) retry the commit, and (b) consider not doing anything else until the error resolves itself (i.e., pressing on will just create more failed commits).

Of course, we can also take the approach that failures are rare enough than any failure should be removed and we can happily pretend as if we never saw it. This seems to be the approach you're taking here. This may be good enough, but I'd like to see more commenting about how exactly this is safe to swallow/ignore.

Let me try to enumerate all the states this class is keeping track of, and see if any can be simplified.

1) Whether we have a valid player, currently determined by mPlayerId == INVALID_PLAYER_ID. Currently this maps to onRequest/onRelease, with the snag that onRequest can be called twice with different IDs.

2) Whether we have a surface view, ie mSurfaceView == null.

3) Whether mSurfaceView is added as child of container view. Currently, this is the same as 2)

4) Whether surface is attached to the media player, ie attach/detachExternalVideoSurface. Nothing explicitly tracks this, so I think right now it might be possible to say call detachExternalVideoSurface twice on the same player id.

A few proposals for you to consider:

a) Split apart 2 and 3, and merge 3 and 4, ie add/remove surface view as child at the same time that the surface is attached/detached from the video player. And also explicitly track this state to avoid repeated calls.

b) Merge 1) and 2). When onRequest is called when mPlayerId is valid, go through all the motions of tearing down the current player, ie detach surface player and remove child, then set mPlayerId to invalid, and release the surface view. Then start from scratch again for the new player.

Then the state machine looks something like:
No player <-> Has player, has surface view, pending surface ready <-> surface ready and attached to player, surface view added as child

I don't feel we should have a UrlDemuxerStream. The way we use it is totally different from a DemuxerStream, so it doesn't pass the "UrlDemuxerStream is a DemuxerStream" test. The "NOTREACHED" in the .cc file demonstrated this as well.

Conceptually, the UrlDemuxerStreamProvider doesn't even need to be a Demuxer either. For example, Seek() on UrlDemuxerStreamProvider doesn't make sense. But I see that currently WMPI and Pipeline* is deeply integrated with Demuxer. Changing that would require a much larger refactoring. So I think UrlDemuxerStreamProvider is fine for now. In the future we can iterate on this.

With that, I wonder whether we can:

1, In DemuxerStreamProvider, in addition to GetStream(), add another method like GetUrl(). The contract will be something like a DemuxerStreamProvider should return non-null for GetStream() (audio and/or video), or non-empty URL for GetUrl(), but not both.

2. Since UrlDemuxerStreamProvider is a Demuxer which is a DemuxerStreamProvider, this should be sufficient for the Renderer to retrieve the URL.

3. With this, I feel DemuxerStreamProvider should be renamed. It's really a "MediaSource" now, but unfortunately that name has been taken. Maybe MediaProvider? Or anything you propose :)

OK, here's a proposed comment:

We block prerendering for anything but search-type matches associated with the default search provider.

This is more restrictive than necessary.  All that's really needed to be able to successfully prerender is that the |destination_url| of |match| be from the same origin and path as the default search engine, and the params to be sent to the server be a subset of the params we can pass to the prerenderer.  So for example, if we normally prerender search URLs like https://google.com/search?q=foo&x=bar, then any match with a URL like that, potentially with the q and/or x params omitted, is prerenderable.

However, if the URL has other params _not_ normally in the prerendered URL, there's no way to pass them to the prerendered page, and worse, if the URL does something like specifying params in both the query and ref sections of the URL (as Google URLs often do), it can quickly become impossible to figure out how to correctly tease out the right param names and values to send.  Rather than try and write parsing code to deal with all these kinds of cases, for various different search engines, including accommodating changing behavior over time, we do the simple restriction described above.  This handles the by-far-the-most-common cases while still being simple and maintainable.

This should work the same way on all platforms: MediaKeys have multiple targets, other keys do not. Here's why:

Lets assume you have two extensions, A and B, that have two wildly differing feature sets. A does a FindInPage replacement, the other replaces all images on the page with cat images. It doesn't make sense to bind the same shortcut (say Ctrl+F) to both of those features because you'd want them mutually exclusive -- It would be weird for all the images to turn to cats *and* the Find box to open at the same time. 

For MediaKeys that's a different story because they have special predefined system functions that are of interest to many extensions. You might have more than one recipient who wants to listen for say VolumeUp (Example: a music app and a video player, to name two). Exclusivity doesn't make sense in that scenario because it would mean you'd have to manually specify who is allowed to receive the event, and switch as you change apps.
